					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">mozz wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Technologies have changed a lot over the last 15 years, and they may also find it safer to do the emulation entirely in software because then if they find a bug in it they only have to fix the software.</div>
<br />
<br />Even if emulation were in hardware, they could work around bugs in the retro games themselves. Remember: Nintendo can "pull a Nesticle" and patch the games rather than fix/improve the emulator, if that's a cheaper approach. They aren't aiming to emulate the NES; they want to emulate <em>specific</em> games. This is much less stringent than modern NES emulators which attempt to emulate NES hardware and (among other things) play the original unmodified game machine code and data.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

